\title{Problem set 4}
\author{}
\date{2025-10-05}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

In the next problem set, we plan to explore the relationship between
COVID-19 death rates and vaccination rates across US states by visually
examining their correlation. This analysis will involve gathering
COVID-19 related data from the CDC's API and then extensively processing
it to merge the various datasets. Since the population sizes of states
vary significantly, we will focus on comparing rates rather than
absolute numbers. To facilitate this, we will also source population
data from the US Census to accurately calculate these rates.

In this problem set we will learn how to extract and wrangle data from
the data US Census and CDC APIs.

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  Get an API key from the US Census at
  \url{https://api.census.gov/data/key_signup.html}. You can't share
  this public key. But your code has to run on a TFs computer. Assume
  the TF will have a file in their working directory named
  \texttt{census-key.R} with the following one line of code:
\end{enumerate}

\begin{verbatim}
census_key <- "A_CENSUS_KEY_THAT_WORKS"
\end{verbatim}

Write a first line of code for your problem set that defines
\texttt{census\_key} by running the code in the file
\texttt{census-key.R}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{source}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"census{-}key.R"}\NormalTok{)}
\CommentTok{\#This line of code tells R to run the census key and loads it.}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\setcounter{enumi}{1}
\tightlist
\item
  The
  \href{https://www.census.gov/content/dam/Census/data/developers/api-user-guide/api-user-guide.pdf}{US
  Census API User Guide} provides details on how to leverage this
  valuable resource. We are interested in vintage population estimates
  for years 2021 and 2022. From the documentation we find that the
  \emph{endpoint} is:
\end{enumerate}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{url }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \StringTok{"https://api.census.gov/data/2021/pep/population"}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Use the \textbf{httr2} package to construct the following GET request.

\begin{verbatim}
https://api.census.gov/data/2021/pep/population?get=POP_2020,POP_2021,NAME&for=state:*&key=YOURKEYHERE
\end{verbatim}

Create an object called \texttt{request} of class
\texttt{httr2\_request} with this URL as an endpoint. Hint: Print out
\texttt{request} to check that the URL matches what we want.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(httr2)}

\NormalTok{url }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\FunctionTok{paste0}\NormalTok{(url,                         }\CommentTok{\#endpoint}
  \StringTok{"?get=POP\_2020,POP\_2021,NAME"}\NormalTok{,          }\CommentTok{\#requested variables, vintage population estimate 2021{-}2022}
  \StringTok{"\&for=state:*"}\NormalTok{,                         }\CommentTok{\#requested range  }
  \StringTok{"\&key="}\NormalTok{, census\_key                     }\CommentTok{\#the local key}
\NormalTok{)}
\CommentTok{\#doing so create the full url that runs on any laptop with the specified key }

\NormalTok{request }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\FunctionTok{request}\NormalTok{(url)                    }\CommentTok{\#create a request}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\setcounter{enumi}{5}
\tightlist
\item
  Examine the \texttt{population} matrix you just created. Notice that
  1) it is not tidy, 2) the column types are not what we want, and 3)
  the first row is a header. Convert \texttt{population} to a tidy
  dataset. Remove the state ID column and change the name of the column
  with state names to \texttt{state\_name}. Add a column with state
  abbreviations called \texttt{state}. Make sure you assign the
  abbreviations for DC and PR correctly. Hint: Use the \textbf{janitor}
  package to make the first row the header.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(tidyverse)}
\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(janitor)}


\NormalTok{population }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ population }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}
  \FunctionTok{row\_to\_names}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{row\_number =} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}                           \CommentTok{\#use first row as header}
  \FunctionTok{as\_tibble}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}                                            \CommentTok{\#turn into tibble}
  \FunctionTok{select}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{state) }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}                                         \CommentTok{\#remove state}
  \FunctionTok{rename}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{state\_name=}\NormalTok{NAME)}\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}                                 \CommentTok{\#rename NAME}
  \FunctionTok{pivot\_longer}\NormalTok{(                                             }\CommentTok{\#turn wide format into long }
    \AttributeTok{cols =} \FunctionTok{starts\_with}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"POP\_"}\NormalTok{),}
    \AttributeTok{names\_to =} \StringTok{"year"}\NormalTok{,}
    \AttributeTok{values\_to =} \StringTok{"population"}
\NormalTok{  ) }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}
  \FunctionTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(                                                   }
    \AttributeTok{year =} \FunctionTok{str\_remove}\NormalTok{(year, }\StringTok{"POP\_"}\NormalTok{),                        }\CommentTok{\#remove the extra characters from year col}
    \AttributeTok{year =} \FunctionTok{as.numeric}\NormalTok{(year),}
    \AttributeTok{population =} \FunctionTok{as.numeric}\NormalTok{(population)                     }
\NormalTok{  ) }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}
  \FunctionTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}
    \AttributeTok{state =} \FunctionTok{case\_when}\NormalTok{(}
\NormalTok{      state\_name }\SpecialCharTok{==} \StringTok{"District of Columbia"} \SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \StringTok{"DC"}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{      state\_name }\SpecialCharTok{==} \StringTok{"Puerto Rico"} \SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \StringTok{"PR"}\NormalTok{,}
      \ConstantTok{TRUE} \SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ state.abb[}\FunctionTok{match}\NormalTok{(state\_name, state.name)]       }\CommentTok{\#state.abb \textless{}{-}returns abbreviation}
                                                            \CommentTok{\#state.name\textless{}{-}has state names}
                                                            \CommentTok{\#both are base R functions}
\NormalTok{    )}
\NormalTok{  )}

\NormalTok{population}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\item
  The following URL:

\begin{Shaded}

points to a JSON file that lists the states in the 10 Public Health
Service (PHS) defined by CDC. We want to add these regions to the
\texttt{population} dataset. To facilitate this create a data frame
called \texttt{regions} that has two columns \texttt{state\_name},
\texttt{region}, \texttt{region\_name}. One of the regions has a long
name. Change it to something shorter.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\setcounter{enumi}{10}
\tightlist
\item
  The reason you see exactly 1,000 rows is because CDC has a default
  limit. You can change this limit by adding
  \texttt{\$limit=10000000000} to the request. Rewrite the previous
  request to ensure that you receive all the data. Then wrangle the
  resulting data frame to produce a data frame with columns
  \texttt{state}, \texttt{date} (should be the end date) and
  \texttt{cases}. Make sure the cases are numeric and the dates are in
  \texttt{Date} ISO-8601 format.
\end{enumerate}

\item
  The dates in the \texttt{cases} dataset are stored as character
  strings. Use the \textbf{lubridate} package to properly parse the
  \texttt{date} column, then create a summary table showing the total
  COVID-19 cases by month and year for 2020 and 2021. The table should
  have columns for year, month (as month name), and total cases across
  all states. Order by year and month. Use the \textbf{knitr} package
  and \texttt{kable()} function to display the results as a formatted
  table.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(lubridate)}
\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(knitr)}
\NormalTok{cases }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}} 
  \FunctionTok{filter}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{year}\NormalTok{(date) }\SpecialCharTok{\%in\%} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{2020}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2021}\NormalTok{)) }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}                \CommentTok{\#filter to only 2020 and 21}
  \FunctionTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{year =} \FunctionTok{year}\NormalTok{(date),}
         \AttributeTok{month =} \FunctionTok{month}\NormalTok{(date)) }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}                          \CommentTok{\#create month and year}
  \FunctionTok{group\_by}\NormalTok{(year,month)}\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}
  \FunctionTok{summarize}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{total=}\FunctionTok{sum}\NormalTok{(cases,}\AttributeTok{na.rm=}\ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{),                  }\CommentTok{\#calculate the sum for each month in each yr}
            \AttributeTok{.groups=}\StringTok{"drop"}\NormalTok{)}\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}
  \FunctionTok{arrange}\NormalTok{(year,month)}\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}                                   \CommentTok{\#order by year and month}
  \FunctionTok{kable}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Use \textbf{httr2} to download COVID-19 death data from this endpoint.
Make sure to remove the default limit to get all available data. Create
a clean dataset called \texttt{deaths} with columns \texttt{state},
\texttt{date}, and \texttt{deaths} (renamed from the original column
name). Ensure dates are in proper Date format and deaths are numeric.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]

  \FunctionTok{req\_url\_query}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textasciigrave{}}\AttributeTok{$limit}\StringTok{\textasciigrave{}} \OtherTok{=} \DecValTok{10000000000}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}     \CommentTok{\#like previous question, set the limit high to grab data}
  \FunctionTok{req\_perform}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}
  \FunctionTok{resp\_body\_json}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{simplifyVector =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{) }

\NormalTok{death }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ deaths\_raw}\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}
  \FunctionTok{select}\NormalTok{(state,end\_date,covid\_19\_deaths)}\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}             \CommentTok{\#select data and rename them}
  \FunctionTok{rename}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{date=}\NormalTok{end\_date,}\AttributeTok{deaths=}\NormalTok{covid\_19\_deaths)}\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}
  \FunctionTok{filter}\NormalTok{(state }\SpecialCharTok{!=} \StringTok{"United States"}\NormalTok{,}\SpecialCharTok{!}\FunctionTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(deaths), }\SpecialCharTok{!}\FunctionTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(date))}\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}}
  \FunctionTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{deaths=}\FunctionTok{as.numeric}\NormalTok{(deaths),}
         \AttributeTok{date=}\FunctionTok{as.Date}\NormalTok{(date))}

\NormalTok{death}
\end{Highlighting}
